s barge his flags are flying: the Tudor rose, the Cornish choughs. Cavendish says, wide-eyed, \x{2018}Look at all these little boats, waffeting up and down.\x{2019} For a moment, the cardinal thinks the Londoners have turned out to wish him well. But as he enters the barge, there are sounds of hooting and booing from the boats; spectators crowd the bank, and though the cardinal's men keep them back, their intent is clear enough. When the oars begin to row upstream, and not downstream to the Tower, there are groans and shouted threats.It is then that the cardinal collapses, falling into his seat, beginning to talk, and talks, talks, talks, all the way to Putney. \x{2018}Do they hate me so much? What have I done but promote their trades and show them my goodwill? Have I sown hatred? No. Persecuted none. Sought remedies every year when wheat was scarce. When the apprentices rioted, begged the king on my knees with tears in my eyes to spare the offenders, while they stood garlanded with the nooses that were to hang them.\x{2019}\x{2018}The multitude,\x{2019} Cavendish says, \x{2018}is always desirous of a change. They never see a great man set up but they must pull him down \x{2013} for the novelty of the thing.\x{2019}\x{2018}Fifteen years Chancellor. Twenty in his service. His father's before that. Never spared myself \x{2026} rising early, watching late \x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}There, you see,\x{2019} Cavendish says, \x{2018}what it is to serve a prince! We should be wary of their vacillations of temper.\x{2019}\x{2018}Princes are not obliged to consistency,\x{2019} he says. He thinks, I may forget myself, lean across and push you overboard.The cardinal has not forgotten himself, far from it; he is looking back, back twenty years to the young king's accession. \x{2018}Put him to work, said some. But I said, no, he is a young man. Let him hunt, joust, and fly his hawks and falcons \x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Play instruments,\x{2019} Cavendish says. \x{2018}Always plucking