ands. \x{2018}When I was small I dreamed of demons. I thought they were under my bed, but you said, it can't be so, you don't get demons our side of the river, the guards won't let them over London Bridge.\x{2019}\x{2018}So are you terrified,\x{2019} Richard says, \x{2018}if you cross the river to Southwark?\x{2019}Gregory says, \x{2018}Southwark? What is Southwark?\x{2019}\x{2018}Do you know,\x{2019} Rafe says, in a schoolmaster's tone, \x{2018}there are times when I see a spark of something in Gregory. Not a blaze, to be sure. Just a spark.\x{2019}\x{2018}That you should mock! With a beard like that.\x{2019}\x{2018}Is that a beard?\x{2019} Richard says. \x{2018}Those scant red bristles? I thought there was some negligence by the barber.\x{2019}They are hugging each other, wild with relief. Gregory says, \x{2018}We thought the king had committed him to some dungeon.\x{2019}Cranmer nods, tolerant, amused. \x{2018}Your children love you.\x{2019}Richard says, \x{2018}We cannot do without the man in charge.\x{2019}It will be many hours till dawn. It is like the lightless morning on which the cardinal died. There is a smell of snow in the air.\x{2018}I suspect he will want us again,\x{2019} Cranmer says. \x{2018}When he has thought about what you have said to him and, shall we say, followed where his thoughts lead him?\x{2019}\x{2018}Still, I shall go back to the city and show my face.\x{2019} Change my clothes, he thinks, and wait for the next thing. To Brereton he says, \x{2018}You know where to find me. William.\x{2019}A nod, and he walks away. \x{2018}Dr Cranmer, tell the Lady we did a good night's work for her.\x{2019} He throws his arm around his son's shoulder, whispers, \x{2018}Gregory, those Merlin stories you read \x{2013} we are going to write some more.\x{2019}Gregory says, \x{2018}Oh, I didn't finish them. The sun came out.\x{2019}Later that day he walks back into a panelled chamber at Greenwich. It is the last day of 1530. He eases off his gloves, kidskin 