ange, Thomas, but since he went, I feel my age. As if I were just a boy, till a few days ago. But God has snapped his fingers, and I see my best years are behind me.\x{2019}\x{2018}You know, after Elizabeth died, my wife \x{2026}\x{2019} And then, he wants to say, my daughters, my sister, my household decimated, my people never out of black, and now my cardinal lost \x{2026} But he will not admit, for even a moment, that sorrow has sapped his will. You cannot get another father, but he would hardly want to; as for wives, they are two-a-penny with Thomas More. \x{2018}You do not believe it now, but feeling will come back. For the world and all you must do in it.\x{2019}\x{2018}You have had your losses, I know. Well, well.\x{2019} The Lord Chancellor sniffs, he sighs, shakes his head. \x{2018}Let us do this necessary thing.\x{2019}It is More who begins to reads him the oath. He swears to give faithful counsel, in his speech to be plain, impartial, in his manner secret, in his allegiance true. He is getting on to wise counsel and discreet, when the door flies opens and Gardiner swoops in, like a crow that's spied a dead sheep. \x{2018}I don't think you can do this without Master Secretary,\x{2019} he says, and Warham says mildly, by the Blessed Rood, must we start swearing him all over again?Thomas Boleyn is stroking his beard. His eye has fallen on the cardinal's ring, and his expression has moved from the shocked to the merely sardonic. \x{2018}If we do not know the procedure,\x{2019} he says, \x{2018}I feel sure Thomas Cromwell has a note of it. Give him a year or two, and we may all find ourselves superfluous.\x{2019}\x{2018}I am sure I shall not live to see it,\x{2019} Warham says. \x{2018}Lord Chancellor, shall we get on? Oh, you poor man! Weeping again. I am very sorry for you. But death comes to us all.\x{2019}Dear God, he thinks, if that's the best you get from the Archbishop of Canterbury, I could do the job.He swears to uphold the king's authorities. His pre