ss \x{2013} and a modest grey worsted gown; Alice receives her gloves and surreptitiously slides in a finger to appraise the silk lining. He rises from his desk and takes her hands, drawing her to the fire and pressing upon her a cup of warm spiced wine. Her hands shake as she cradles the cup and she says, \x{2018}I wish John had this. This wine. This fire.\x{2019}It was snowing at dawn on the day of the raid on Lion's Quay, but soon a wintery sun was up, scouring windowpanes and casting the panelled rooms of city houses into sharp relief, ravines of shadows and cold floods of light. \x{2018}That is what I cannot get out of my mind,\x{2019} Lucy says, \x{2018}the cold.\x{2019} And More himself, his face muffled in furs, standing at the door with his officers, ready to search the warehouse and their own rooms. \x{2018}I was the first there,\x{2019} she says, \x{2018}and I kept him hovering with pleasantries \x{2013} I called up, my dear, here is the Lord Chancellor come on parliamentary business.\x{2019} The wine floods into her face, loosens her tongue. \x{2018}I kept saying, have you breakfasted, sir, are you sure, and the servants were weaving under his feet, impeding him\x{2019} \x{2013} she gives a little, mirthless, whooping laugh \x{2013} \x{2018}and all the time John was stowing his papers behind a panel \x{2013}\x{2019}\x{2018}You did well, Lucy.\x{2019}\x{2018}When they walked upstairs John was ready for him \x{2013} oh, Lord Chancellor, welcome to my poor house \x{2013} but the poor hapless man, he had cast his Testament under his desk, my eye went straight to it, I wonder their eyes didn't follow mine.\x{2019}An hour's search realised nothing; so are you sure, John, the Chancellor said, that you have none of these new books, because I was informed you had? (And Tyndale lying there, like a poison stain on the tiles.) I don't know who could have told you that, said John Petyt. I was proud of him, Lucy says, holding out her cup for more wine, I was proud that he spoke up. More said, it is true I have found nothing today, but you must go with these men. Mr Lieutenant, will you take him?John Petyt is not a young man. At More's direction he sleeps on a pad of straw laid on the flagstones; visitors have been admitted only so that they can take back to his neighbours the news of how ill he looks. \x{2018}We have sent food and warm clothes,\x{2019} Lucy says, \x{2018}and been turned away on the Lord Chancellor's orders.\x{2019}\x{2018}There's a tariff for bribes. You pay the gaolers. You need ready money?\x{2019}\x{2018}If I do I shall come to you.\x{2019} She puts the cup down on his desk. \x{2018}He cannot lock us all up.\x{2019}\x{2018}He has prisons enough.\x{2019}\x{2018}For bodies, yes. But what are bodies? He can take our goods, but God will prosper us. He can close the booksellers, but still there will be books. They have their old bones, their glass saints in windows, their candles and shrines, but God has given us the printing press.\x{2019} Her cheeks glow. She glances down to the drawings on his desk. \x{2018}What are these, Master Cromwell?\x{2019}\x{2018}The plans for my garden. I am hoping to buy some of the houses at the back of here, I want the land.\x{2019}She smiles. \x{2018}A garden \x{2026} It is the first pleasant thing I have heard of in a while.\x{2019}\x{2018}I hope you and John will come and enjoy it.\x{2019}\x{2018}And this \x{2026} You are going to build a tennis court?\x{2019}\x{2018}If I get the ground. And here, you see, I mean to plant an orchard.\x{2019}Tears well into her eyes. \x{2018}Speak to the king. We count on you.\x{2019}He hears a footstep: Johane's. Lucy's hand flies to her mouth. \x{2018}God forgive me \x{2026} For a moment I took you for your sister.\x{2019}\x{2018}The mistake is made,\x{2019} Johane says. \x{2018}And sometimes persists. Mistress Petyt, I am very sorry to hear your husband is in the Tower. But you have brought this on yourselves. You people were the first to throw