tartled, to being ambushed. Anne, waking out of her dream, says, \x{2018}What did you just do?\x{2019}\x{2018}Hit Mark. Only,\x{2019} he demonstrates, \x{2018}with one finger.\x{2019}Anne says, \x{2018}Mark? Who? Oh. Is that his name?\x{2019}This spring, 1531, he makes it his business to be cheerful. The cardinal was a great grumbler, but he always grumbled in some entertaining way. The more he complained, the more cheerful his man Cromwell became; that was the arrangement.The king is a complainer too. He has a headache. The Duke of Suffolk is stupid. The weather is too warm for the time of year. The country is going to the dogs. He's anxious too; afraid of spells, and of people thinking bad thoughts about him in any specific or unspecific way. The more anxious the king becomes, the more tranquil becomes his new servant, the more hopeful, the more staunch. And the more the king snips and carps, the more do his petitioners seek out the company of Cromwell, so unfailing in his amiable courtesy.At home, Jo comes to him looking perplexed. She is a young lady now, with a womanly frown, a soft crinkle of flesh on her forehead, which Johane her mother has too. \x{2018}Sir, how shall we paint our eggs at Easter?\x{2019}\x{2018}How did you paint them last year?\x{2019}\x{2018}Every year before this we gave them hats like the cardinal's.\x{2019} She watches his face, to read back the effect of her words; it is his own habit exactly, and he thinks, not only your children are your children. \x{2018}Was it wrong?\x{2019}\x{2018}Not at all. I wish I'd known. I would have taken him one. He would have liked it.\x{2019}Jo puts her soft little hand into his. It is still a child's hand, the skin scuffed over the knuckles, the nails bitten. \x{2018}I am of the king's council now,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}You can paint crowns if you like.\x{2019}This piece of folly with her mother, this ongoing folly, it has to stop. Johane knows it too. She used to make excuses, to be where he was. But