 The word maschio is painted on the outside, and inside are pictures of plump blond-haired babies, each with a coy little phallus. She laughs. The Italians say for a boy you have to keep warm, he tells her. Heat up your wine to heat up your blood. No cold fruit, no fish.Jane Seymour says, \x{2018}Do you think it's already decided, what it will be, or does God decide later? Do you think it knows itself, what it is? Do you think if we could see inside you, we would be able to tell?\x{2019}\x{2018}Jane, I wish you were still down in Wiltshire,\x{2019} Mary Shelton says.Anne says, \x{2018}You needn't cut me up, Mistress Seymour. It is a boy, and no one is to say or think otherwise.\x{2019} She frowns, and you can see her bending, concentrating, the great force of her will.\x{2018}I'd like a baby,\x{2019} Jane says.\x{2018}Watch yourself,\x{2019} Lady Rochford tells her. \x{2018}If your belly shows, mistress, we'll have you bricked up alive.\x{2019}\x{2018}In her family,\x{2019} Anne says, \x{2018}they'd give her a bouquet. They don't know what continence means, down at Wolf Hall.\x{2019}Jane is flushed and trembling. \x{2018}I meant no harm.\x{2019}\x{2018}Leave her,\x{2019} Anne says. \x{2018}It's like baiting a fieldmouse.\x{2019} She turns to him. \x{2018}Your bill is not passed yet. Tell me what is the delay.\x{2019}The bill, she means, to forbid appeals to Rome. He begins to explain to her the strength of the opposition, but she raises her eyebrows and says, \x{2018}My father is speaking for you in the Lords, and Norfolk. So who dare oppose us?\x{2019}\x{2018}I shall have it through by Easter, depend upon it.\x{2019}\x{2018}The woman we saw in Canterbury, they say her people are printing a book of her prophecies.\x{2019}\x{2018}That may be, but I shall make sure no one reads it.\x{2019}\x{2018}They say on St Catherine's Day last, while we were at Calais, she saw a vision of the so-called princess Mary crowned queen.\x{2019} Her voice runs on, fluid, rapid, these are my enemies, this prophetess and those about her, Katherine who is plotting with the Emperor, her daughter Mary the supposed heir, Mary's old governess Margaret Pole, Lady Salisbury, she and all her family are my enemies, her son Lord Montague, her son Reginald Pole who is abroad, people talk of his claim to the throne so why can he not be brought back, his loyalty examined? Henry Courtenay, the Marquis of Exeter, he believes he has a claim, but when my son is born that will put him out of his conceit. Lady Exeter, Gertrude, she is forever complaining that noblemen are being put down from their places by men of low birth, and you know who she means by that.My lady, her sister says softly, do not distress yourself.I am not distressed, Anne says. Her hand over the growing child, she says calmly, \x{2018}These people want me dead.\x{2019}The days are still short, the king's temper shorter. Chapuys bows and writhes before him, twisting and grimacing, as if he had in mind to ask Henry to dance. \x{2018}I have read with some perplexity certain conclusions reached by Dr Cranmer \x{2013}\x{2019}\x{2018}My archbishop,\x{2019} the king says coldly; at great expense, the anointing has taken place.\x{2018}\x{2013} conclusions regarding Queen Katherine \x{2013}\x{2019}\x{2018}Who? You mean my late brother's wife, the Princess of Wales?\x{2019}\x{2018}\x{2013} for Your Majesty knows that dispensations were issued in such form as to allow your own marriage to be valid, whether or no that former marriage was consummated.\x{2019}\x{2018}I do not want to hear the word dispensation,\x{2019} Henry says. \x{2018}I do not want to hear you mention what you call my marriage. The Pope has no power to make incest licit. I am no more Katherine's husband than you are.\x{2019}Chapuys bows.\x{2018}If the contract had not been void,\x{2019} Henry says, patient for the last time, \x{2018}God would not have punished me with the loss of my children.\x{2019}\x{2018}We do not know the blessed Katherine is beyond childbearing.\x{2019} He looks up with a sly, delicate glance.\x{2018}Tell me, why do you think I do this?\x{2019} The king sounds curious. \x{2018}Out of lust? Is that what you think?\x{2019}Kill a cardinal? Divide your country? Split the church? \x{2018}It seems extravagant,\x{2019} Chapuys murmurs.\x{2018}But that is what you think. That is what you tell the Emperor. You are wrong. I am the steward of my country, sir, and if I now take a wife in a union blessed by God, it is to have a son by her.\x{2019}\x{2018}But there is no guarantee that Your Majesty will have a son. Or any living children at all.\x{2019}\x{2018}Why would I not?\x{2019} Henry reddens. He is on his feet, shouting, angry tears spilling down his face. \x{2018}Am I not a man like other men? Am I not? Am I not?\x{2019}He is a game little terrier, the Emperor's man; but even he knows that when you've made a king cry it's time to back off. On the way out he says \x{2013} dusting himself down, with his accustomed, self-deprecatory flutter \x{2013} \x{2018}There is a distinction to be drawn between the welfare of the country and the welfare of the Tudor line. Or do you not think so?\x{2019}\x{2018}So who is your preferred candidate for the throne? You favour Courtenay, or Pole?\x{2019}\x{2018}You should not sneer at persons of royal blood.\x{2019} Chapuys shakes out his sleeves. \x{2018}At least now I am officially informed of the lady's state, whereas before I could only deduce it from certain spectacles of folly I had witnessed \x{2026} Do you know how much you are staking, Cremuel, on the body of one woman? Let us hope no evil comes near her, eh?\x{2019}He takes the ambassador by the arm, wheels him around. \x{2018}What evil? Say what you mean.\x{2019}\x{2018}If you would let go your grip on my jacket. Thank you. Very soon you resort to manhandling people, which shows, as they say, your breeding.\x{2019} His words are full of bravado, but he is trembling. \x{2018}Look around you and see how by her pride and her presumption she offends your own nobility. Her own uncle has no stomach for her tricks. The king's oldest friends make excuses to stay away from court.\x{2019}\x{2018}Wait till she's crowned,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}Watch them come running.\x{2019}On 12 April, Easter Sunday, Anne appears with the king at High Mass, and is prayed for as Queen of England. His bill went through Parliament just yesterday; he expects a modest reward, and before the royal party go in to break their fast, the king waves him over and gives him Lord Berners's old post, chancellor of the exchequer. \x{2018}Berners suggested you for it.\x{2019} Henry smiles. He likes giving; like a child, he enjoys anticipating how pleased you will be.During Mass, his mind had wandered through the city. What noisome goose houses have they waiting for him at home? What rows in the street, what babies left on church steps, what unruly apprentices with whom he will please have a word? Have Alice and Jo painted Easter eggs? They are too grown up now, but they are content to be the children of the house until the next generation comes along. It's time he put his mind to husbands for them. Anne, if she had lived, could be married by now, and to Rafe, as he is still not spoken for. He thinks of Helen Barre; how fast she gets on with her reading, how they cannot do without her at Austin Friars. He believes now that her husband is dead, and he thinks, I must talk to her, I must tell her she is free. She is too proper to show any pleasure, but who would not like to know that she is no longer subject to a man like that?Through Mass, Henry keeps up a constant buzz of talk. He sorts papers and passes them up and down to his councillors; only at the consecration does he throw himself to his knees in a fever of reverence, as the miracle takes place and a wafer becomes God. As soon as the priest says, \x{2018}Ita, missa est,\x{2019} he whispers, come to me in my closet, alone.First the assembled courtiers must make their bows to Anne. Her ladies sweep back and leave her alone in a little sunlit space. He watches them, watches the gentlemen and councillors, among whom, on this feast day, are many of the king's boyhood friends. He watches Sir Nicholas Carew in particular; nothing is wanting in his reverence to his new queen, but he cannot help a downturn of his mouth. Arrange your face, Nicholas Carew, your ancient family face. He hears Anne saying, these are my enemies: he adds Carew to the list.Behind the chambers of state are the king's own rooms, which only his intimates see, where he is served by his gentlemen, and where he can be free of ambassadors and spies. This is Henry Norris's ground, and Norris gently congratulates him on his new appointment, and moves away, soft-footed.\x{2018}You know Cranmer is to convene a court to make a formal dissolution of the \x{2026}\x{2019} Henry has said he does not want to hear any more about his marriage, so he will not even say the word. \x{2018}I have asked him to convene at the priory at Dunstable, because it is, what, ten, twelve miles to Ampthill, where she is lodged \x{2013} so she can send her lawyers, if she likes. Or come to the court herself. I want you to go to see her, go secretly, just talk to her \x{2013}\x{2019}Make sure she springs no surprises.\x{2018}Leave Rafe with me while you are gone.\x{2019} At being so easily understood, the king relaxes into good humour. \x{2018}I can rely on him to say what Cromwell would say. You have a good boy there. And he is better than you are at keeping his face straight. I see you, when we sit in council, with your hand before your mouth. Sometimes, you know, I want to laugh myself.\x{2019} He drops into a chair, covers his face as if to shade his eyes. He sees that, once again, the king is about to cry. \x{2018}Brandon says my sister is dying. There is no more the doctors can do for her. You know that fair hair she had once, hair like silver \x{2013} my daughter had that. When she was seven she was the image of my sister, like a saint painted on a wall. Tell me, what am I to do with my daughter?\x{2019}He waits, till he knows it is a real question. \x{2018}Be good to her, sir. Conciliate her. She should not suffer.\x{2019}\x{2018}But I must make her a bastard. I need to settle England on my lawful children.\x{2019}\x{2018}Parliament will do it.\x{2019}\x{2018}Yes.\x{2019} He sniffs. Scrubs his tears away. \x{2018}After Anne is crowned. Cromwell, one thing, and then we will have our breakfast, because I am really very hungry. This project of a match for my cousin Richard \x{2026}\x{2019}He thinks his way, rapidly, around the nobility of England. But no, he sees it's his Richard, Richard Cromwell. \x{2018}Lady Carey \x{2026}\x{2019} The king's voice softens. \x{2018}Well, I have thought it over, and I think, no. Or at least, not at this time.\x{2019}He nods. He understands his reason. When Anne understands it, she will spit nails.\x{2018}Sometimes it is a solace to me,\x{2019} Henry says, \x{2018}not to have to talk and talk. You were born to understand me, perhaps.\x{2019}That is one view of their situations. He was six years or so in this world before Henry came into it, years of which he made good use. Henry takes off his embroidered cap, throws it down, runs his hands through his hair. Like Wyatt's golden mane, his hair is thinning, and it exposes the shape of his massive skull. For a moment he seems like a carved statue, like a simpler form of himself, or one of his own ancestors: one of the race of giants that roamed Britain, and left no trace of themselves except in the dreams of their petty descendants.He goes back to Austin Friars as soon as he can get away. Surely he can have one day off? The crowds outside his gate have dispersed, as Thurston has fed them an Easter dinner. He goes out to the kitchen first, to give his man a slap on the head and a gold piece. \x{2018}A hundred open maws, I swear,\x{2019} Thurston says. \x{2018}And by supper time they'll be round again.\x{2019}\x{2018}It is a shame there should be beggars.\x{2019}\x{2018}Beggars my arse. What comes out of this kitchen is so good, there are aldermen out there, with their hoods up so we don't know them. And I have a houseful here, whether you are with us or not \x{2013} I have Frenchmen, Germans, I have Florentiners, they all claim to know you and they all want their dinner to their own liking, I have their servants down here, pinch of that, soup\x{e7}on of the other. We must feed fewer, or build another kitchen.\x{2019}\x{2018}I'll get it in hand.\x{2019}\x{2018}Master Rafe says for the Tower you have bought out the whole of a quarry in Normandy. He says the Frenchmen are all undermined, and dropping into holes in the ground.\x{2019}Such beautiful stone. The colour of butter. Four hundred men on the payroll, and anyone standing about instantly redeployed to the building work at Austin Friars. \x{2018}Thurston, don't let anybody put pinches or soup\x{e7}ons in our dinner.\x{2019} He thinks, that's how Bishop Fisher nearly died; unless it was an unboiled stockpot after all. You could never fault Thurston's stockpot. He goes and views it, bubbling away. \x{2018}Where is Richard, do you know?\x{2019}\x{2018}Chopping onions on the back step. Oh, you mean Master Richard? Upstairs. Eating. Where's anybody?\x{2019}He goes up. The Easter eggs, he sees, bear his own unmistakable features. Jo has painted his hat and his hair in one, so he seems to be wearing a cap with ear-flaps. She has given him at least two chins. \x{2018}Well, sir,\x{2019} Gregory says, \x{2018}it is true you are getting stout. When Stephen Vaughan was here he could not believe you.\x{2019}\x{2018}My master the cardinal waxed like the moon,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}It is a mystery, because he hardly sat down to dine but he would be leaping up to deal with some exigency, and even when he was at the table he could hardly eat for talking. I feel sorry for myself. I have not broken bread since last night.\x{2019} He breaks it, and says, \x{2018}Hans wants to paint me.\x{2019}\x{2018}I hope he can run fast,\x{2019} Richard says.\x{2018}Richard \x{2013}\x{2019}\x{2018}Have your dinner.\x{2019}\x{2018}My breakfast. No, never mind it. Come.\x{2019}\x{2018}The happy bridegroom,\x{2019} Gregory says, taunting.\x{2018}You,\x{2019} his father threatens him, \x{2018}are going north with Rowland Lee. If you think I'm a hard man, wait till you meet Rowland.\x{2019}In his office, he says, \x{2018}How is your practice in the lists?\x{2019}\x{2018}Good. Cromwells will knock down all-comers.\x{2019}He is afraid for his son; that he will fall, be maimed, be killed. Afraid for Richard too; these boys are the hope of his house. Richard says, \x{2018}So am I? The happy bridegroom?\x{2019}\x{2018}The king says no. It is not because of my family, or your family \x{2013} he calls you his cousin. He is, at this moment, his disposition to us, I would say it is excellent. But he needs Mary for himself. The child is due in late summer and he is afraid to touch Anne. And he does not wish to resume his celibate life.\x{2019}Richard looks up. \x{2018}He said this?\x{2019}\x{2018}He left me to understand it. And as I understand it, I convey it to you, and we are both amazed, but we get over it.\x{2019}\x{2018}I suppose if the sisters were more alike, one could begin to understand it.\x{2019}\x{2018}I suppose,\x{2019} he says, \x{2018}one could.\x{2019}\x{2018}And he is the head of our church. No wonder foreigners laugh.\x{2019}\x{2018}If he were a model of conduct in his private life, one would be \x{2026} surprised \x{2026} but for me, you see, I can only concern myself with his kingship. If he were oppressive, if he were to override Parliament, if he were to pay no heed to the Commons and govern only for himself \x{2026} But he does not \x{2026} so I cannot concern myself with how he behaves to his women.\x{2019}\x{2018}But if he were not king \x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Oh, I agree. You'd have him locked up. But again, Richard, leave aside Mary and he has behaved well enough. He hasn't filled a nursery with his bastards, as the Scottish kings do. There have been women, but who can name them? Only Richmond's mother, and the Boleyns. He has been discreet.\x{2019}\x{2018}I dare say Katherine knew their names.\x{2019}\x{2018}Who can say he will be a faithful husband? Will you?\x{2019}\x{2018}I may not get the chance.\x{2019}\x{2018}On the contrary, I have a wife for you. Thomas Murfyn's girl? A Lord Mayor's daughter is not a bad prospect. And your fortune will more than match hers, I will make sure of that. And Frances likes you. I know because I have asked her.\x{2019}\x{2018}You have asked my wife to marry me?\x{2019}\x{2018}Since I was dining there yesterday \x{2013} no point in delay, was there?\x{2019}\x{2018}Not really.\x{2019} Richard laughs. He stretches back in his chair. His body \x{2013} his capable, admirable body, which has impressed the king so much \x{2013} is rinsed with relief. \x{2018}Frances. Good. I like Frances.\x{2019}Mercy approves. He cannot think how she would have taken to Lady Carey; he had not broached the topic with the women. She says, \x{2018}Don't leave it too long to make a match for Gregory. He is very young, I know. But some men never grow up until they have a son of their own.\x{2019}He hasn't thought about it, but it might be true. In that case, there's hope for the kingdom of England.Two days later he is back at the Tower. The time goes quickly between Easter and Whit, when Anne will be crowned. He inspects her new apartments and orders in braziers to help dry out the plaster. He wants to get on with the frescoes \x{2013} he wishes Hans would come down, but he is painting de Dinteville and says he needs to push on with it, as the ambassador is petitioning Francis for his recall, a whining letter on every boat. For the new queen we are not going to have those hunting scenes you see painted everywhere, or grim virgin saints with the instruments of their torture, but goddesses, doves, white falcons, canopies of green leaves. In the distance, cities seated on the hills: in the foreground, temples, groves, fallen columns and hot blue skies delineated, as within a frame, by borders of Vitruvian colours, quicksilver and cinnabar, burnt ochre, malachite, indigo and purple. He unrolls the sketches the craftsmen have made. Minerva's owl spreads her wings across a panel. A barefoot Diana fits an arrow to her bow. A white doe watches her from the trees. He scribbles a direction to the overseer: Arrow to be picked out in gold. All goddesses have dark eyes. Like a wingtip from the dark, dread brushes him: what if Anne dies? Henry will want another woman. He will bring her to these rooms. Her eyes may be blue. We will have to scour away the faces and paint them again, against the same cities, the same violet hills.Outside he stops to watch a fight. A stonemason and the bricklayer's gaffer are swiping at each other with battens. He stands in the ring with the trowel men. \x{2018}What's it about?\x{2019}\x{2018}Nuffing. Stone men have to fight brick men.\x{2019}\x{2018}Like Lancaster and York?\x{2019}\x{2018}Like that.\x{2019}\x{2018}Have you ever heard of the field called Towton? The king tells me more than twenty thousand Englishmen died.\x{2019}The man gapes at him. \x{2018}Who were they fighting?\x{2019}\x{2018}Each other.\x{2019}It was Palm Sunday, the year 1461. The armies of two kings met in the driving snow. King Edward the king's grandfather was the winner, if you can say there was a winner at all. Corpses made a bobbing bridge across the river. Uncounted numbers crawled away, rolled and tumbled in their own blood: some blinded, some disfigured, some maimed for life.The child in Anne's womb is the guarantee of no more civil war. He is the beginning, the start of something, the promise of another country.He walks into the fight. He bellows at them to stop. He gives them both a push and they bowl over backwards: two crumbly Englishmen, snappable bones, chalky teeth. Victors of Agin-court. He's glad Chapuys isn't there to see.* * *The trees are in full leaf when he rides into Bedfordshire, with a small train on unofficial business. Christophe rides beside him and pesters him: you have said you will tell me who is Cicero, and who is Reginald Pole.\x{2018}Cicero was a Roman.\x{2019}\x{2018}A general?\x{2019}\x{2018}No, he left that to others. As I, for example, might leave it to Norfolk.\x{2019}\x{2018}Oh, Norferk.\x{2019} Christophe subjects the duke to his peculiar pronunciation. \x{2018}He is one who pisses on your shadow.\x{2019}\x{2018}Dear God, Christophe! I've heard of spitting on someone's shadow.\x{2019}\x{2018}Yes, but we speak of Norferk. And Cicero?\x{2019}\x{2018}We lawyers try to memorise all his speeches. If any man were walking around today with all of Cicero's wisdom in his head he would be \x{2026}\x{2019} He would be what? \x{2018}Cicero would be on the king's side,\x{2019} he says.Christophe is not much impressed. \x{2018}Pole, he is a general?\x{2019}\x{2018}A priest. That is not quite true \x{2026} He has offices in the church, but he has not been ordained.\x{2019}\x{2018}Why not?\x{2019}\x{2018}No doubt so he can marry. It is his blood that makes him dangerous. He is a Plantagenet. His brothers are here in this kingdom under our eye. But Reginald is abroad and we are afraid he is plotting with the Emperor.\x{2019}\x{2018}Send one to kill him. I will go.\x{2019}\x{2018}No, Christophe, I need you to stop the rain spoiling my hats.\x{2019}\x{2018}As you wish.\x{2019} Christophe shrugs. \x{2018}But I will kill a Pole when you require it, it will be my pleasure.\x{2019}The manor at Ampthill, once fortified, has airy towers and a splendid gatehouse. It stands on a hill with views over wooded countryside; it is a pleasant seat, the kind of house you'd visit after an illness to get your strength back. It was built with money gained in the French wars, in the days when the English used to win them.To accord with Katherine's new status as Dowager Princess of Wales, Henry has trimmed her household, but still she is surrounded by chaplains and confessors, by household officers each with their own train of menials, by butlers and carvers, physicians, cooks, scullions, maltsters, harpers, lutenists, poultry keepers, gardeners, laundresses, apothecaries, and an entourage of wardrobe ladies, bedchamber ladies and their maids. But when he is ushered in she nods to her attendants to withdraw. No one had told her to expect him, but she must have spies on the road. Hence her nonchalant parade of occupation: a prayer book in her lap, and some sewing. He kneels to her, nods towards these encumbrances. \x{2018}Surely, madam, one or the other?\x{2019}\x{2018}So, English today? Get up, Cromwell. We will not waste our time, as at our last interview, selecting which language to use. Because nowadays you are such a busy man.\x{2019}Formalities over, she says, \x{2018}First thing. I shall not attend your court at Dunstable. That is what you have come to find out, is it not? I do not recognise this court. My case is at Rome, awaiting the attention of the Holy Father.\x{2019}\x{2018}Slow, isn't he?\x{2019} He gives her a puzzled smile.\x{2018}I will wait.\x{2019}\x{2018}But the king wishes to settle his affairs.\x{2019}\x{2018}He has a man who will do it. I do not call him an archbishop.\x{2019}\x{2018}Clement issued the bulls.\x{2019}\x{2018}Clement was misled. Dr Cranmer is a heretic.\x{2019}\x{2018}Perhaps you think the king is a heretic?\x{2019}\x{2018}No. Only a schismatic.\x{2019}\x{2018}If a general council of the church were called, His Majesty would submit to its judgment.\x{2019}\x{2018}It will be too late, if he is excommunicate, and put outside the church.\x{2019}\x{2018}We all hope \x{2013} I am sure you do, madam \x{2013} that day will never come.\x{2019}\x{2018}Nulla