ut I reason \x{2026} do not you, Lord Chancellor \x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Oh, he does,\x{2019} the duke says. \x{2018}Whatever you reason, Tom, he reasons. Squawk, squawk.\x{2019}Wriothesley looks startled. \x{2018}Could I bring Will in?\x{2019}\x{2018}So we are united? On our knees to beg?\x{2019}\x{2018}I won't do it unless Cranmer will,\x{2019} the duke says. \x{2018}Why should a layman wear out his joints?\x{2019}\x{2018}Shall we send for my lord Suffolk too?\x{2019} Audley suggests.\x{2018}No. His boy is dying. His heir.\x{2019} The duke scrubs his hand across his mouth. \x{2018}He wants just a month of his eighteenth birthday.\x{2019} His fingers fidget for his holy medals, his relics. \x{2018}Brandon's got the one boy. So have I. So have you, Cromwell. And Thomas More. Just the one boy. God help Charles, he'll have to start breeding again with his new wife; that'll be a hardship to him, I'm sure.\x{2019} He gives a bark of laughter. \x{2018}If I could pension my lady wife off, I could get a juicy fifteen-year-old too. But she won't go.\x{2019}It is too much for Audley. His face flushes. \x{2018}My lord, you have been married, and well married, these twenty years.\x{2019}\x{2018}Do I not know it? It's like placing your person in a grizzled leather bag.\x{2019} The duke's bony hand descends; he squeezes his shoulder. \x{2018}Get me a divorce, Cromwell, will you? You and my lord archbishop, come up with some grounds. I promise there'll be no murder done over it.\x{2019}\x{2018}Where is murder done?\x{2019} Wriothesley says.\x{2018}We're preparing to murder Thomas More, aren't we? Old Fisher, we're whetting the knife for him, eh?\x{2019}\x{2018}God forbid.\x{2019} The Lord Chancellor rises, sweeping his gown around him. \x{2018}These are not capital charges. More and the Bishop of Rochester, they are only accessories.\x{2019}\x{2018}Which,\x{2019} Wriothesley says, \x{2018}in all conscience is grave enough.\x{2019}Norfolk shrugs. \x{2018}Kill them now or later. More won't take your oath. Fisher won't.\x{2019}\x{2018}I am quite sure they will,\x{2019} Audley says. \x{2018}We shall use efficacious persuasions. No reasonable man will refuse to swear to the succession, for the safety of this realm.\x{2019}\x{2018}So is Katherine to be sworn,\x{2019} the duke says, \x{2018}to uphold the succession of my niece's infant? What about Mary \x{2013} is she to be sworn? And if they will not, what do you propose? Draw them to Tyburn on a hurdle and hang them up kicking, for their relative the Emperor to see?\x{2019}He and Audley exchange a glance. Audley says, \x{2018}My lord, you shouldn't drink so much wine <<before noon|13>>.\x{2019}\x{2018}Oh, tweet, tweet,\x{2019} the duke says.A week ago he had been up to Hatfield, to see the two royal ladies: the princess Elizabeth, and Lady Mary the king's daughter. \x{2018}Make sure you get the titles right,\x{2019} he had said to Gregory as they rode.Gregory had said, \x{2018}Already you are wishing you had brought Richard.\x{2019}He had not wanted to leave London during such a busy parliament, but the king persuaded him: two days and you can be back, I want your eye on things. The route out of the city was running with thaw water, and in copses shielded from the sun the standing pools were still iced. A weak sun blinked at them as they crossed into Hertfordshire, and here and there a ragged blackthorn blossomed, waving at him a petition against the length of winter.\x{2018}I used to come here years ago. It was Cardinal Morton's place, you know, and he would leave town when the law term was over and the weather was getting warm, and when I was nine or ten my uncle John used to pack me in a provisions cart with the best cheeses and the pies, in case anybody tried to steal them when we stopped.\x{2019}\x{2018}Did you not have guards?\x{2019}\x{2018}It was the guards he was afraid of.\x{2019}\x{2018}Quis custodiet ipsos custodes?\x{2019}\x{2018}Me, evidently.\x{2019}\x{2018}What would you have done?\x{2019}\x{2018}I don't know. Bitten them?\x{2019}The mellow brick frontage is smaller than he remembers, but that is what memory does. These pages and gentlemen running out, these grooms to lead away the horses, the warmed wine that awaits them, the noise and the fuss, it is a different sort of arrival from those of long ago. The portage of wood and water, the firing up the ranges, these tasks were beyond the strength or skill of a child, but he was unwilling to concede them, and worked alongside the men, grubby and hungry, till someone saw that he was about to fall over: or until he actually did.Sir John Shelton is head of this strange household, but he has chosen a time when Sir John is from home; talk to the women, is his idea, rather than listen to Shelton after supper on the subjects of horses, dogs and his youthful exploits. But on the threshold, he almost changes his mind; coming downstairs at a rapid, creaking scuttle is Lady Bryan, mother of one-eyed Francis, who is in charge of the tiny princess. She is a woman of nearly seventy, well bedded into grand-maternity, and he can see her mouth moving before she is within range of his hearing: Her Grace slept till <<eleven|9f>>, squalled till <<midnight|13>>, exhausted herself, poor little chicken! fell asleep an hour, woke up grizzling, cheeks scarlet, suspicion of fever, Lady Shelton woken, physician aroused, teething already, a treacherous time! soothing draught, settled by sun-up, woke at <<nine|9b>>, took a feed \x{2026} \x{2018}Oh, Master Cromwell,\x{2019} Lady Bryan says, \x{2018}this is never your son! Bless him! What a lovely tall young man! What a pretty face he has, he must get it from his mother. What age would he be now?\x{2019}\x{2018}Of an age to talk, I believe.\x{2019}Lady Bryan turns to Gregory, her face aglow as if at the prospect of sharing a nursery rhyme with him. Lady Shelton sweeps in. \x{2018}Give you good day, masters.\x{2019} A small hesitation: does the queen's aunt bow to the Master of the Jewel House? On the whole she thinks not. \x{2018}I expect Lady Bryan has given you a full account of her charge?\x{2019}\x{2018}Indeed, and perhaps we could have an account of yours?\x{2019}\x{2018}You will not see Lady Mary for yourself?\x{2019}\x{2018}Yes, but forewarned \x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Indeed. I do not go armed, though my niece the queen recommends I use my fists on her.\x{2019} Her eyes sweep over him, assessing; the air crackles with tension. How do women do that? One could learn it, perhaps; he feels, rather than sees, his son back off, till his regress is checked by the cupboard displaying the princess Elizabeth's already extensive collection of gold and silver plate. Lady Shelton says, \x{2018}I am charged that, if the Lady Mary does not obey me, I should, and here I quote you my niece's words, beat her and buffet her like the bastard she is.\x{2019}\x{2018}Oh, Mother of God!\x{2019} Lady Bryan moans. \x{2018}I was Mary's nurse too, and she was stubborn as an infant, so she'll not change now, buffet her as you may. You'd like to see the baby first, would you not? Come with me \x{2026}\x{2019} She takes Gregory into custody, hand squeezing his elbow. On she rattles: you see, with a child of that age, a fever could be anything. It could be the start of the measles, God forbid. It could be the start of the smallpox. With a child of six months, you don't know what it could be the start of \x{2026} A pulse is beating in Lady Bryan's throat. As she chatters she licks her dry lips, and swallows.He understands now why Henry wanted him here. The things that are happening cannot be put in a letter. He says to Lady Shelton, \x{2018}Do you mean the queen has written to you about Lady Mary, using these terms?\x{2019}\x{2018}No. She has passed on a verbal instruction.\x{2019} She sweeps ahead of him. \x{2018}Do you think I should implement it?\x{2019}\x{2018}We will perhaps speak in private,\x{2019} he murmurs.\x{2018}Yes, why not?\x{2019} she says: a tu