s, and if Parliament trespassed on God's law \x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}On the Pope's law, he means \x{2013} for he holds them the same, he couldn't deny that, could he? Why is he always examining his conscience, if not to check day and night that it is in accord with the church of Rome? That is his comfort, that is his guide. It seems to me, if he plainly denies Parliament its capacity, he denies the king his title. Which is treason. Still,\x{2019} he shrugs, \x{2018}how far does it take us? Can we show the denial was malicious? He will say, I suppose, that it was just talk, to pass the time. That you were putting cases, and that anything said in that wise cannot be held against a man.\x{2019}\x{2018}A jury won't understand that. They'll take him to mean what he said. After all, sir, he knew it wasn't some students' debate.\x{2019}\x{2018}True. You don't hold those at the Tower.\x{2019}Riche offers the memorandum. \x{2018}I have written it down faithfully to the best of my recollection.\x{2019}\x{2018}You don't have a witness?\x{2019}\x{2018}They were in and out, packing up the books in a crate, he had a lot of books. You cannot blame me for carelessness, sir, for how was I to know he would talk to me at all?\x{2019}\x{2018}I don't blame you.\x{2019} He sighs. \x{2018}In fact, Purse, you are the apple of my eye. You'll stand behind this in court?\x{2019}Doubtful, Riche nods. \x{2018}Tell me you will, Richard. Or tell me you won't. Let's have it straight. Have the grace to say so now, if you think your courage might fail. If we lose another trial, we can kiss goodbye to our livelihoods. And all our work will be for nothing.\x{2019}\x{2018}You see, he couldn't resist it, the chance to put me right,\x{2019} Riche says. \x{2018}He will never let it drop, what I did as a boy. He uses me to make his sermon on. Well, let him make his next sermon on the block.\x{2019}The evening before Fisher is to die, he visits More. He takes a strong guard with him, but he leaves them in t